  "opinion": "As a 45-year-old hairdresser in Kansas City, I see fake content on social media like a bad haircut—it's everywhere, and it can really mess things up if you don't handle it right. I'm on social media a few times a week, mostly to share my birdwatching photos or chat about movies, but I've learned to spot the fakes pretty quick. With my high openness, I'm curious about new stuff, but my low conscientiousness means I don't always dig deep into every post. Being extraverted, I love connecting with people, but my moderate agreeableness makes me skeptical when something seems off. I'm anxious by nature, so fake news about health or safety really gets to me, but my low neuroticism helps me stay calm and not overreact. To manage fake content, I start by checking the source—if it's from some random page with no real info, I ignore it. I also look for other posts or news sites to confirm things, especially since I only have a primary school education and rely on my parents' master's degrees for advice sometimes. As an Atheist, I'm used to questioning beliefs, so I apply that to social media too. I report fake posts when I can, and I talk to my kid about it, teaching them to think critically. In my hobbies like painting and board games, I value authenticity, and I bring that to online spaces. It's all about staying alert without letting it ruin the fun of connecting with others.",
